  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate the exponential function \\( f(x) = a^x \\) up to the fourth derivative, we'll apply the differentiation rules for exponential functions. Here's a step-by-step breakdown:\n\n### 1. **First Derivative (\\( f'(x) \\))**\n\nThe first derivative of \\( a^x \\) with respect to \\( x \\) is:\n\n\\[\nf'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( a^x \\right) = a^x \\ln(a)\n\\]\n\n**Explanation:**  \nThe derivative of \\( a^x \\) is \\( a^x \\) multiplied by the natural logarithm of \\( a \\).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Second Derivative (\\( f''(x) \\))**\n\nDifferentiating the first derivative:\n\n\\[\nf''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( a^x \\ln(a) \\right) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2\n\\]\n\n**Explanation:**  \nEach differentiation introduces another factor of \\( \\ln(a) \\), so the second derivative includes \\( (\\ln(a))^2 \\).\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Third Derivative (\\( f'''(x) \\))**\n\nDifferentiating the second derivative:\n\n\\[\nf'''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( a^x (\\ln(a))^2 \\right) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3\n\\]\n\n**Explanation:**  \nContinuing the pattern, the third derivative has \\( (\\ln(a))^3 \\).\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Fourth Derivative (\\( f''''(x) \\))**\n\nDifferentiating the third derivative:\n\n\\[\nf''''(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} \\left( a^x (\\ln(a))^3 \\right) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4\n\\]\n\n**Explanation:**  \nThe fourth derivative incorporates \\( (\\ln(a))^4 \\).\n\n---\n\n### **Summary of Derivatives**\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align*}\nf(x) &= a^x \\\\\nf'(x) &= a^x \\ln(a) \\\\\nf''(x) &= a^x (\\ln(a))^2 \\\\\nf'''(x) &= a^x (\\ln(a))^3 \\\\\nf''''(x) &= a^x (\\ln(a))^4 \\\\\n\\end{align*}\n\\]\n\n### **General Pattern**\n\nThe \\( n \\)-th derivative of \\( f(x) = a^x \\) is:\n\n\\[\nf^{(n)}(x) = a^x (\\ln(a))^n\n\\]\n\n**Key Point:**  \nEach time you differentiate \\( a^x \\), you multiply by an additional \\( \\ln(a) \\). This results in the \\( n \\)-th derivative being \\( a^x \\) multiplied by \\( (\\ln(a))^n \\).\n\n---\n\n### **Example**\n\nSuppose \\( a = 2 \\) and you want to find the fourth derivative of \\( f(x) = 2^x \\):\n\n\\[\nf''''(x) = 2^x (\\ln(2))^4\n\\]\n\n---\n\nFeel free to ask if you need more information or further clarification!",
